La Croix Double Blind Study Power Analysis

Chris Mellinger

4/26/2018

experiment <- setClass(
  "experiment",
  slots = c(pVals = "numeric", propSig = "numeric")
)

runExperiments <- function (nTrials, numExperiments, successRate, nullRate) {
  # Generate data for each experiment
  rawData <- replicate(numExperiments, rbinom(1, nTrials, successRate))
  
  # Test to see if the difference is significant.
  pVals <- sapply(
    rawData,
    function (studyResult) {
      test <- binom.test(studyResult, nTrials, nullRate)
      return(test$p.value)
    }
  )
  propSig <- mean(pVals <= .05)
  
  # Create an object
  exp <- experiment(pVals = pVals, propSig = propSig)
  return(exp)
}

# Print method
print.experiment <- function (exp) {print(paste("Proportion of significant experiments:", round(exp@propSig, 3)))}

# Plot method
plot.experiment <- function (exp, ...) {
  hist(
    exp@pVals,
    xlab = "p-values",
    ...
  )
}

Power Simulations

These simulations assume a design where a single judge identifies the flavor of a beverage by choosing from 4 different options. Thus, the null is 25% accuracy (chance responding).

50% Accurate Judge

10 trials:

exp50_10 <- runExperiments(10, 10000, .50, .25)
print(exp50_10)
## [1] "Proportion of significant experiments: 0.381"
plot(exp50_10, breaks = 50)

That is not enough.

20 trials:

exp50_20 <- runExperiments(20, 10000, .50, .25)
print(exp50_20)
## [1] "Proportion of significant experiments: 0.594"
plot(exp50_20)

Not quite.

30 trials:

exp50_30 <- runExperiments(30, 10000, .50, .25)
print(exp50_30)
## [1] "Proportion of significant experiments: 0.816"
plot(exp50_30)

There it is!

75% Accurate Judge

Lets assume the same design, but with a 75% accurate judge.

exp75_5 <- runExperiments(5, 10000, .75, .25)
print(exp75_5)
## [1] "Proportion of significant experiments: 0.636"
plot(exp75_5, breaks = 50)

exp75_10 <- runExperiments(10, 10000, .75, .25)
print(exp75_10)
## [1] "Proportion of significant experiments: 0.921"
plot(exp75_10, breaks = 50)

Conclusion

In a single-judge design, 30 trials are required to detect an accuracy of 50%, but only 10 trials to detect accuracy of 75%. My conclusion is that 30 trials is preferable. Given that our judges actually enjoy drinking this beverage, it seems more ethical to instantiate this participant (non?) burden in the interest of more reliable estimates.
